{
  "title": "Containerizing CLI Tools Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to create a Docker container to encapsulate Command Line Interface (CLI) tools utilizing FastAPI, an modern, efficient, and flexible web framework for building APIs in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "Setup development environment with Python 3.12+, FastAPI, Uvicorn ASGI server, and Docker.",
    "Create a simple CLI tool (script) as a starting point for containerization.",
    "Write a FastAPI application that exposes the CLI tool's functionality via HTTP endpoints.",
    "Package the application and its dependencies using Dockerfile.",
    "Implement container execution using `uvicorn.run()` within the Dockerfile, enabling automatic invocation of the CLI tool upon container startup.",
    "Push the built container image to a container registry (e.g., Docker Hub) for easy deployment."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "```\n# Create Dockerfile\ndocker\nFROM python:3.12-slim\n\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y tzdata\n\nARG APP_NAME=myapp\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY . $APP_NAME\n\nRUN pip install fastapi uvicorn\n\nCMD [\"uvicorn\", \"$APP_NAME:app\", \"--host\", \"0.0.0.0\", \"--port\", \"8000\"]\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nimport sys\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\ndef cli():\n # Your CLI tool code here\n\n@app.get('/')\ndef index():\n sys.argv += ['run', '--host', '0.0.0.0', '--port', '8000']\nsys.exit(cli())\n```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "This explainer is specifically tailored for Python 3.12+.",
    "Ensure your system has Docker installed before following the instructions."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "The provided code examples are simplified and may require modifications based on your specific CLI tool's requirements.",
    "Make sure to secure your FastAPI application by implementing appropriate authentication and authorization mechanisms."
  ]
}
